{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "The usual interpretation of Bose-Einstein correlations (BEC) of identical boson pairs relates the width of the peak in the correlation function at small relative four-momentum to the spatial extent of the source of the bosons. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "However, in the \u03c4-model, which successfully describes BEC in hadronic Z decay, the width of the peak is related to the temporal extent of boson emission. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "Some new checks on the validity of both the \u03c4-model and the usual descriptions are presented.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "First a brief review of 'classic' parametrizations of Bose-Einstein Correlations (BEC) is given and contrasted with the parametrization of the \u03c4-model [1,2]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 151,
                    "end": 154,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 154,
                    "end": 156,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "which has been found [3] to describe well Bose-Einstein correlations in hadronic Z decay.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 21,
                    "end": 24,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The data used in this paper are taken from Ref. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "[3]. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "They comprise both two-jet and threejet events, as determined using the Durham jet algorithm [4][5][6] with resolution parameter y cut =0.006, from e + e \u2212 annihilation at the Z-pole.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 93,
                    "end": 96,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[4]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 96,
                    "end": 99,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "[5]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 99,
                    "end": 102,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The Bose-Einstein correlation function, R 2 , is measured by R 2 (Q) = \u03c1(Q)/\u03c1 0 (Q), where \u03c1(Q) is the density of identical boson pairs with invariant four-momentum difference Q = \u2212(p 1 \u2212 p 2 ) 2 and \u03c1 0 (Q) is the similar density in an artificially constructed reference sample, which should differ from the data only in that it does not contain the effects of Bose symmetrization of identical bosons. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "It is often parametrized as",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "with",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The corresponding distribution of boson emission points in space-time is a spherically symmetric Gaussian with standard deviation r. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The factor (1 + Q) is included to account for non-BEC which are not removed by \u03c1 0 , i.e., to make up for slight inadequacies in \u03c1 0 , and \u03b3 is a normalization parameter. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The parameter \u03bb is introduced to account for effects reducing the amount of BEC, e.g., some of the bosons coming from resonance decays, or the identical bosons being partially coherent.",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "However, this description was found [3] not to describe the Z-decay data, a better description being provided by the Edgeworth expansion about the Gaussian [7]:",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 36,
                    "end": 39,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 156,
                    "end": 159,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "where H 3 is the third-order Hermite polynomial.",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "A different way to depart from the Gaussian is the generalization to a symmetric L\u00e9vy stable distribution. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Then",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "where 0 < \u03b1 \u2264 2 is the so-called index of stability, which was introduced to BEC in Ref. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "[8].",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A fit of the Edgeworth parametrization to the two-jet data of Ref. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "[3] finds \u03ba = 0.71\u00b10.06, while a fit of the symmetric L\u00e9vy parametrization yields \u03b1 = 1.34 \u00b1 0.04. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Both values are far from the corresponding Gaussian values of \u03ba = 0 and \u03b1 = 2, respectively. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Although the \u03c7 2 of these fits are a great improvement over that of the Gaussian fit, they are still very large. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The corresponding confidence levels are 10 \u221215 for the Gaussian and 10 \u22125 and 10 \u22128 for the Edgeworth and L\u00e9vy fits, respectively. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The symmetric L\u00e9vy fit is shown in Fig. 1a. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 35,
                    "end": 42,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1a"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The reason for the failure of the 'classic' parametrizations is readily apparent from Fig. 1a. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 86,
                    "end": 93,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1a"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "There is a region of anti-correlation (R 2 < 1) extending from about Q = 0.5 to 1.5 GeV. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The 'classic' parametrizations, which are of the form 1+ P, where P is a positive-definite quantity, are unable to accomadate the anti-correlation. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "This was not realized for a long time because experiments only plotted the correlation function up to Q = 2 GeV or less. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "In Ref. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "[3] Q was plotted to 4 GeV, and the anti-correlation became apparent. ",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This anti-correlation, which one might term Bose-Einstein Anti-Correlations (BEAC), as well as the Bose-Einstein correlations (BEC) are both well described by the \u03c4-model.",
            "section": "'Classic' Parametrizations",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The \u03c4-model",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The \u03c4-model [1,2] rests on several assumptions:",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 12,
                    "end": 15,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 15,
                    "end": 17,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The average production point is proportional to the momentum of the emitted boson. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Dimensionally the momentum must be multiplied by a time divided by a mass to yield a spatial dimension. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The description of a two-jet event is invariant to Lorentz boosts along the direction of the colour field. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The relevant boost-invariant quantities are the \"longitudinal\" proper time, \u03c4 = t 2 \u2212 r 2 z and the \"transverse\" mass, m",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The spatial distribution of production points about their mean is very narrow, although the distribution of proper time may be broad.",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 The distribution of \u03c4 is a one-sided L\u00e9vy distribution, one-sided because no particles are emitted before the e + e \u2212 collision.",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Then R 2 turns out to depend on three variables, Q and the transverse mass of each of the particles making up the pair:",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 16,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Fits in three dimensions are problematic with the available statistics. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Hence we simplify this expression by introducing an effective radius, R, defined by",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 17,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Further, we assume that particle production begins immediately, i.e., \u03c4 0 = 0. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Then",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 18,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The fit of the simplified \u03c4-model to the two-jet data is shown in Fig. 1b. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 66,
                    "end": 73,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1b"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Unlike the fits of the classic parametrizations, the \u03c7 2 is acceptable, and the residuals lack structure. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Note that the difference between the parametrizations of Eqs. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "(4) and 8is the presence of the cosine term, which provides the description of the BEAC dip. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "(4)"
                },
                {
                    "start": 8,
                    "end": 9,
                    "ref_id": "formula_7",
                    "text": "8"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The parameter R describes the BEC peak, and R a describes the anti-correlation region. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "While one might have had the insight to add, ad hoc, a cos term to Eq. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "(4), it is the \u03c4-model which provides a physical reason for it and which predicts a relationship, Eq. ",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "(8b), between R and R a , i.e., between the correlation and the anti-correlation.",
            "section": "The \u03c4-model",
            "paragraph_rank": 19,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Expansions",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Recall that the Edgeworth expansion of the Gaussian parametrization provided evidence (in addition to the poor \u03c7 2 ) that the Gaussian was inadequate. ",
            "section": "Expansions",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "In this section we look at expansions of the Symmetric L\u00e9vy and the \u03c4-model parametrizations.",
            "section": "Expansions",
            "paragraph_rank": 20,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "section_rank": 6,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 10,
                    "end": 14,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "L\u00c3\u00a9vy",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The symmetric L\u00e9vy distribution can be expanded in terms of L\u00e9vy polynomials [9,10], l i , which are orthonormal. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 77,
                    "end": 80,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[9,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 80,
                    "end": 83,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "10]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The resulting expression for R 2 is",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 21,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Fits to the two-jet data are shown in Fig. 2a for orders 0 through 3 of the L\u00e9vy polynomials. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 38,
                    "end": 45,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 2a"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The order-0 fit (also shown in Fig. 1a) has a very poor \u03c7 2 , but the order-1 fit has a good \u03c7 2 .",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 22,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 31,
                    "end": 38,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1a"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Higher orders show only marginal further improvement.",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 23,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "(a) ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "(b) Figure 2. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 4,
                    "end": 12,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Figure 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "(a) Symmetric L\u00e9vy fit for two-jet events up to orders 0 through 3 L\u00e9vy polynomials; ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "(b) First-order L\u00e9vy polynomial fit (black) for two-jet events compared to the \u03c4-model fit (red).",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 24,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The first-order symmetric L\u00e9vy polynomial fit is shown together with the simplified \u03c4model fit in Fig. 2b. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 98,
                    "end": 105,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 2b"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The \u03c7 2 of the L\u00e9vy polynomial fit is slightly better than the \u03c4-model fit, but the fit curves are nearly identical, what difference there is being mainly for Q > 1.5 GeV.",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 25,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Comparing Eqs. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "(8) and 9, we see that in the symmetric L\u00e9vy parametrization the cosine of the \u03c4-model parametrization is replaced by the L\u00e9vy polynomial expansion. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "(8)"
                },
                {
                    "start": 8,
                    "end": 9,
                    "ref_id": "formula_9",
                    "text": "9"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Also, in the exponential 2\u03b1 becomes simply \u03b1. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig. 3 compares the cosine and the L\u00e9vy polynomials. ",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 6,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "We see a rather similar behaviour: Both decrease more or less linearly with Q, which explains why both fit the data approximately equally well.",
            "section": "Symmetric L\u00e9vy",
            "paragraph_rank": 26,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "section_rank": 7,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 1,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "\u00cf\u0084",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Lacking an orthogonal polynomial expansion for the asymmetric L\u00e9vy distribution H(\u03c4) of the \u03c4-model, we use, motivated by the results of Ref. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "[9], a derivative expansion: We also consider letting R a be a free parameter rather than as defined in Eq. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[9]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "(8b). ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The results of these fits are shown in Table 1 and Fig. 4a. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 39,
                    "end": 46,
                    "type": "table",
                    "ref_id": "tab_0",
                    "text": "Table 1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 51,
                    "end": 58,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 4a"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The \u03c7 2 of the order-1 fit is, of course, smaller than that of the order-0 fit, as is the R a -free fit, and the confidence levels are somewhat better.",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 27,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "To test the significance of the improvement in \u03c7 2 , we make use of the \u03c7 2 -difference. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "For the order-0 and order-1 fits this is \u03c7 2 diff = 94.7 \u2212 90.9 = 3.8, and the difference in the number of degrees of freedom is 1. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The confidence level for a \u03c7 2 of 3.8 with 1 degree of freedom is 5.1%. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "A small value of this confidence level, say less than 5%, would be grounds for rejecting the order-0 parametrization. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "(This corresponds to the 95% commonly used in making decisions.) ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus we conclude that for two-jet events the order-0 fit is adequate.",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 28,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "The order-0, R a -free fit also provides an adequate description, having a \u03c7 2 nearly identical to that of the order-1, R a -constrained fit. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Note that the physical parameters (\u03b1, R, \u03bb) differ at most by about 1 standard deviation in going from order-0 to order-1 or to R a free. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus conclusions based on these values, such as the reconstructions of the space-time picture in Ref. ",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 7
        },
        {
            "text": "[3], remain valid.",
            "section": "\u03c4-model (asymmetric L\u00e9vy)",
            "paragraph_rank": 29,
            "section_rank": 7,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "We have used expansions about the hypothesized form to test whether it provides an adequate description of the data or is only a (poor) approximation. ",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 30,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "In the latter case the shape of the expansion terms provide an indication of how to modify the original parametrization. ",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 30,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "For the symmetric L\u00e9vy parametrization this showed that an approximately linearly decreasing function of Q is necessary, which in fact is what is provided by the \u03c4-model.",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 30,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "An expansion in the case of the \u03c4-model is found not to be significant, i.e., the one-sided L\u00e9vy distribution of the \u03c4-model is adequate.  ",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 31,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 4. ",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 31,
            "section_rank": 8,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Figure 4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "(a) Fits of the \u03c4-model (black), the order-1 expansion of the \u03c4-model (red), and the \u03c4-model with R a free (green), for two-jet events; ",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 31,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "(b) Fits of the \u03c4-model (black), the order-1 expansion of the \u03c4-model (red), the \u03c4-model with R a free (green), and the order-1 expansion of the \u03c4-model with R a free (blue), for three-jet events.",
            "section": "Conclusions for two-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 31,
            "section_rank": 8
        },
        {
            "text": "Three-jet events",
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "For two-jet events hadronization occurs basically in 1+1 dimensions, which lead to the dependence of R 2 on \u03c4, the longitudinal proper time and m t , the transverse mass. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 32,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "For three-jet events, the qqg system no longer forms a linear system (in the overall centre of mass), but a planar one. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 32,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "There is no event axis by which the transverse mass and longitudinal proper time are defined. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 32,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Therefore we might expect the \u03c4-model, as formulated for a two-jet system, to work less well.",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 32,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "The results of fits of the \u03c4-model and its first-order expansion, without and with R a a free parameter, are shown in Fig. 4b and Table 2. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 33,
            "section_rank": 9,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 118,
                    "end": 125,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 4b"
                },
                {
                    "start": 130,
                    "end": 137,
                    "type": "table",
                    "text": "Table 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Applying the \u03c7 2 -difference test to the order-0 and order-1 fits yields a confidence level of 37% for the case that R a is constrained and 58% when R a is free.",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 33,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "However, the \u03c7 2 -difference between the order-0 R a constrained and free cases yields a confidence level of 6 \u2022 10 \u22128 . ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus regarding R a as a free parameter does give significant improvement.",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 34,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "But it must be pointed out that the parameters R a and \u03c4 0 are expected to be highly correlated. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "While for two-jet events it was found in Ref. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "[3] that \u03c4 0 is consistent with zero, such studies have not yet been performed for three-jet events. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 3,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Further investigation is ongoing. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Also, note that the value of \u03b1 is significantly less for the fits with R a free than for those with R a constrained. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "This was not the case for two-jet events. ",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "This too requires additional investigation.",
            "section": "Three-jet events",
            "paragraph_rank": 35,
            "section_rank": 9
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 1 .",
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 1. ",
            "section": "Figure 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "(a) Symmetric L\u00e9vy fit for two-jet events; ",
            "section": "Figure 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "(b) Simplified \u03c4-model fit for two-jet events.",
            "section": "Figure 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 36,
            "section_rank": 10
        },
        {
            "text": "\u03bb\u03c4Figure 3 .",
            "section_rank": 11
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 3. ",
            "section": "\u03bb\u03c4Figure 3 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 37,
            "section_rank": 11
        },
        {
            "text": "Comparison of the cosine term of the \u03c4-model parametrization with the L\u00e9vy polynomial term of the symmetric L\u00e9vy parametrization.",
            "section": "\u03bb\u03c4Figure 3 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 37,
            "section_rank": 11
        },
        {
            "text": "Table 1 .",
            "section_rank": 12
        },
        {
            "text": "Fit results of \u03c4-model parametrizations for two-jet events.",
            "section": "Table 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 38,
            "section_rank": 12
        },
        {
            "text": "EPJ Web of Conferences 206, 03004 (2019) https://doi.org/10.1051/epjconf/201920603004 ISMD 2018",
            "section": "Table 1 .",
            "paragraph_rank": 39,
            "section_rank": 12,
